╭─ Assistant [MainThread@262586] ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ An analysis of the bug report indicates that the SLP vectorizer is crashing due to an      │
│ assertion failure: `TEPtr->UserTreeIndices.size() == 1 && "Expected only single user of a  │
│ gather node."`. This assertion is located in the `isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry`     │
│ function and suggests that a `TreeEntry` representing a scalar broadcast (a "gather" node) │
│ has been incorrectly assigned multiple users within the SLP-tree, which is an invalid      │
│ state.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause lies in the `BoUpSLP::buildTree_rec` function. When constructing the        │
│ vectorization tree, the vectorizer may encounter a scalar value that is used by multiple   │
│ instructions within the same vectorization candidate. The logic for handling such reused   │
│ scalars is flawed. Specifically, when a scalar operand is encountered that is already part │
│ of an existing `TreeEntry`, the current user is added to the `TreeEntry`'s user list.      │
│ However, the code fails to check if this user has already been added, leading to duplicate │
│ entries in the user list. This occurs when multiple lanes of a vector operation use the    │
│ same scalar operand.                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to introduce a check before adding a new user to a `TreeEntry`. By using the    │
│ `isUser()` method, we can ensure that we do not add the same user-operand pair multiple    │
│ times. This maintains the integrity of the SLP-tree data structure and prevents the        │
│ subsequent assertion failure.                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The change is made in `BoUpSLP::buildTree_rec`, where a scalar operand is identified as    │
│ being part of an existing `TreeEntry`. The original code unconditionally added the new     │
│ user, which is now guarded by a check for pre-existence.                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ @@ -8240,8 +8240,8 @@                                                                      │
│        // bundle.                                                                          │
│        TE = It->second;                                                                    │
│        // If the user is not this entry, add it to the list of users.                      │
│ -      if (TE->getSingleUser() != Entry)                                                   │
│ -        TE->addUser(Entry, OpIdx);                                                        │
│ +      if (!TE->isUser(Entry, OpIdx))                                                      │
│ +         TE->addUser(Entry, OpIdx);                                                       │
│      } else {                                                                              │
│        // The operand is a new scalar.                                                     │
│        TE = newTreeEntry({V}, std::nullopt /*not vectorized*/, S, {Entry, OpIdx});         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
